# =============================================================================
# Simula Training Implementation Agent Rules
# Path: src/training/.clinerules
# =============================================================================

Purpose
- Make `src/training` the authoritative implementation of the Simula training-data framework.
- Drive the codebase to full spec compliance, not partial library-level alignment.
- Treat this file as the standing execution contract for any agent working on Simula implementation, maintenance, integration, or migration tasks.

Mission
- Implement the Simula specification end to end across runner, contracts, evaluation, API integration, and frontend integration.
- Replace legacy-by-default behavior with Simula-by-default behavior.
- Keep the system operationally honest: no placeholder telemetry, no synthetic preview data for governed production runs, and no claims of completion while the live path still runs the old pipeline.

Source Of Truth
- Normative product spec:
  - `docs/pdf/specs/simula-training-spec.pdf`
  - `docs/latex/specs/simula/chapters/03-extraction-pipeline.tex`
  - `docs/latex/specs/simula/chapters/04-taxonomy-engine.tex`
  - `docs/latex/specs/simula/chapters/05-generation-engine.tex`
  - `docs/latex/specs/simula/chapters/06-environment-cli.tex`
  - `docs/latex/specs/simula/chapters/07-references.tex`
  - `docs/latex/specs/simula/chapters/12-implementation-instructions.tex`
- Normative data contracts:
  - `docs/schema/simula/training-example.schema.json`
  - `docs/schema/simula/taxonomy.schema.json`
- Current implementation reality:
  - `src/training/scripts/run_hana_pipeline.py`
  - `src/training/pipeline/hana_schema_extractor.py`
  - `src/training/pipeline/simula_taxonomy_builder.py`
  - `src/training/pipeline/simula_data_generator.py`
  - `src/training/pipeline/simula_complexity_calibrator.py`
  - `src/training/pipeline/simula_coverage_evaluator.py`
  - `src/training/pipeline/simula_critic_validator.py`
  - `src/training/pipeline/simula_diversity_analyzer.py`
  - `src/training/pipeline/simula_diversity_optimizer.py`
  - `src/training/pipeline/simula_taxonomy_evaluator.py`
  - `src/training/pipeline/main.py`
  - `src/training/pipeline/Makefile`
  - `src/training/Makefile`
- Operational integration points outside `src/training` that must be considered whenever end-to-end compliance is the goal:
  - `src/generativeUI/training-webcomponents-ngx/packages/api-server/src/main.py`
  - `src/generativeUI/training-webcomponents-ngx/apps/angular-shell/src/app/pages/pipeline/pipeline.component.ts`
  - `src/generativeUI/training-webcomponents-ngx/apps/angular-shell/src/app/pages/hana-explorer/hana-explorer.component.ts`
  - `src/generativeUI/training-webcomponents-ngx/apps/angular-shell/src/app/components/shell/shell.component.ts`

Read First On Every Simula Task
1. Read the relevant spec chapter before changing code.
2. Read the relevant JSON schema before changing any model or serialized artifact.
3. Read the current runner and current live integration path before assuming a module is already in production.
4. Identify whether the task is:
   - contract repair
   - runner/orchestration
   - evaluator integration
   - API integration
   - frontend integration
   - monitoring/alerting
5. Only then edit code.

Current Repo Reality You Must Assume
- The current default runtime path is still legacy, centered on:
  - `src/training/pipeline/main.py`
  - `src/training/pipeline/Makefile`
  - `src/training/Makefile`
  - `training-webcomponents-ngx` API worker commands
- The Simula modules exist, but they are not yet the authoritative live path.
- The evaluation layer is only partially integrated and some modules currently drift from the actual runtime models.
- Passing legacy tests does not prove Simula compliance.

Known Issue Registry
- `SIM-KI-001` legacy path still default:
  - symptom: pipeline launches `make all`, legacy template expansion, or `training/pipeline/output/train.jsonl`
  - impact: production path is not running the spec-defined Simula flow
  - prevention: default entrypoints, API worker, and UI stage model must all point to the Simula runner
- `SIM-KI-002` contract drift between runtime models and schemas:
  - symptom: evaluator modules expect fields not present on `TrainingExample` or taxonomy objects
  - impact: coverage, critic validation, and downstream evaluation crash at runtime
  - prevention: schema-first model changes, plus producer and consumer updates in the same change
- `SIM-KI-003` preview and synthetic fallback masquerading as operational behavior:
  - symptom: HANA or data preview surfaces return preview/synthetic data while the product appears healthy
  - impact: operators can mistake demo behavior for production success
  - prevention: explicit mode labeling and governed-run fail-closed behavior
- `SIM-KI-004` simulated UI telemetry:
  - symptom: random throughput, fake stage timing, or placeholder run signals in production surfaces
  - impact: false confidence, poor incident diagnosis
  - prevention: bind UI telemetry to real runtime artifacts, logs, and job state

Primary Goal State
- The default pipeline path launches the Simula HANA-direct flow.
- Every generated artifact follows one canonical contract shared by runner, API, governance, and frontend.
- The evaluation framework runs on every completed Simula generation run.
- Governed runs never silently degrade into preview/demo behavior.
- Runtime surfaces show real execution state and real artifacts.

10/10 Definition Of Done
- `src/training/scripts/run_hana_pipeline.py` or an equivalent Simula runner is the authoritative default entrypoint.
- The live API launches the same Simula runner, not legacy `make all` or legacy schema/template generators.
- The pipeline implements the spec phases:
  - extraction: MCP discovery, table enumeration, column extraction, registry population, JSON export
  - taxonomy: factor identification, breadth-first expansion, best-of-N proposal, critic refinement, level planning
  - generation: mix sampling, meta-prompt generation, complexification, example generation, double-critic filtering
  - evaluation: complexity calibration, coverage, diversity, critic calibration, taxonomy quality, and any required adaptive logic/reporting
- `TrainingExample` artifacts validate against `docs/schema/simula/training-example.schema.json`.
- Taxonomy artifacts validate against `docs/schema/simula/taxonomy.schema.json`.
- Every run emits the stable artifact set required by Chapter 6:
  - `schemas.json`
  - `taxonomies.json`
  - `training_data.jsonl`
  - `generation_stats.json`
  - `rejected_examples.jsonl`
  - `complexity_elo_scores.json`
  - `coverage_report.json`
  - `diversity_metrics.json`
  - `critic_calibration.json`
- Evaluator modules execute without contract drift or runtime exceptions.
- Governance captures run status plus evaluator outcomes.
- Frontend surfaces the real Simula artifacts and evaluation results.
- Preview mode is clearly marked as non-production and is never treated as healthy for governed production runs.

Non-Negotiable Engineering Rules
1. Prefer the Simula spec over legacy behavior when they conflict.
2. Preserve the legacy pipeline only as an explicit compatibility path, never as the default path.
3. Keep one canonical contract for:
   - `TrainingExample`
   - taxonomy tree and node structure
   - evaluation reports
   - runner outputs
   - API payloads
   - frontend artifact expectations
4. If you add, remove, or rename a serialized field, update all producers, consumers, tests, and schemas in the same change.
5. Do not create hidden compatibility shims that let modules disagree on core field names.
6. Do not treat timestamped output filenames as the only canonical output contract. If timestamped files are needed, also materialize stable canonical names or manifests.
7. Do not ship placeholder or random telemetry for production monitoring surfaces.
8. Do not let governed runs rely on synthetic preview data except in an explicit demo path that is clearly labeled and segregated.
9. Do not mark Simula complete just because library modules exist. The default live path must use them.

Canonical Contract Rules
- `TrainingExample` must be schema-first. At minimum, the runtime contract must support the required schema fields:
  - `id`
  - `question`
  - `sql`
  - `complexity_score`
  - `critic_passed`
- The broader implementation should support the schema-defined Simula fields needed for evaluation and traceability, including:
  - `schema_context`
  - `taxonomy_path`
  - `mix_id`
  - `complexity_level`
  - `elo_rating`
  - `is_complexified`
  - `critic_evaluation`
  - `generation_metadata`
  - `quality_signals`
- Taxonomy artifacts must expose schema-compatible identifiers and structure, including:
  - `taxonomy_id`
  - `name`
  - `root`
  - node-level `node_id`
  - node `path`
  - statistics and generation metadata
- If code and schema disagree, assume the code is wrong unless the spec has been explicitly revised.

Required Runtime And Output Behavior
- The authoritative runner must produce a stable artifact set in the agreed output directory.
- The runner must fail loudly for these conditions:
  - zero extracted tables
  - zero taxonomies
  - zero examples
  - missing required artifacts
  - evaluator contract drift
  - evaluator runtime exceptions
- The runner must record enough metadata for governance and debugging:
  - config used
  - timestamps
  - counts by stage
  - failure reason when unsuccessful

Evaluation And Quality Gates
- Complexity calibration must run and emit an Elo-based report.
- Coverage evaluation must run against the generated taxonomies.
- Diversity analysis must emit both global and local diversity metrics.
- Critic validation must measure both acceptance of correct samples and rejection of corrupted samples.
- Taxonomy quality evaluation must be emitted when the taxonomy schema or spec requires it.
- Adaptive controls described in the spec must be real runtime behavior, not dead helper methods.

Default Threshold Expectations
- Critic calibration target:
  - `p(accept | correct) > 0.80`
  - `p(accept | corrupted) < 0.30`
- Taxonomy quality targets from schema:
  - completeness target: `> 0.70`
  - soundness target: `> 0.90`
- Coverage and diversity thresholds must be explicit in code or config, not implied by comments alone.

Required Integration Rules
- If you change the runner contract, update the API worker in:
  - `src/generativeUI/training-webcomponents-ngx/packages/api-server/src/main.py`
- If you change pipeline stages, artifact names, or run semantics, update the frontend pipeline page in:
  - `src/generativeUI/training-webcomponents-ngx/apps/angular-shell/src/app/pages/pipeline/pipeline.component.ts`
- If you change live-vs-preview behavior, update:
  - `src/generativeUI/training-webcomponents-ngx/apps/angular-shell/src/app/pages/hana-explorer/hana-explorer.component.ts`
  - `src/generativeUI/training-webcomponents-ngx/apps/angular-shell/src/app/components/shell/shell.component.ts`
- Do not leave the UI/API pointing at legacy paths after changing the backend.

Priority Order For Bringing The System To 10/10
1. Make the Simula runner the authoritative default path.
2. Repair `TrainingExample`, taxonomy, and evaluator contract drift against the JSON schemas.
3. Normalize artifact names and locations across runner, API, governance, and frontend.
4. Integrate the full evaluation framework into the operational run.
5. Replace placeholder telemetry and preview-first behavior in the live product surfaces.
6. Only then remove or quarantine remaining legacy defaults.

Pre-Change Checklist
- Confirm which spec chapter is being implemented.
- Confirm which JSON schema contracts are affected.
- Confirm whether the change touches only `src/training` or also requires API/frontend integration updates.
- Check whether the current live path still references:
  - `make all`
  - `schema_pipeline/data_generator.py`
  - `prepare_training_data.py`
  - `training/pipeline/output/train.jsonl`
- Check whether the UI still references legacy stage names or synthetic telemetry.
- If any of those are still present in the impacted path, treat migration work as part of the task, not optional follow-up.

Task Checklist For Any Non-Trivial Change
- Confirm which spec chapter governs the task.
- Confirm which serialized contracts are touched.
- Confirm whether API and frontend consumers are affected.
- Add or update tests before declaring completion.
- Run the narrowest meaningful test set plus at least one end-to-end smoke path for the changed contract.
- Report any remaining spec gaps explicitly.

Minimum Verification Before Closing Work
- If training models or artifacts changed:
  - validate against `docs/schema/simula/training-example.schema.json`
  - validate against `docs/schema/simula/taxonomy.schema.json` when relevant
- If runner or pipeline wiring changed:
  - run the runner entrypoint used by the live API path
  - verify required output files exist
- If evaluator code changed:
  - run evaluator-specific tests
  - run at least one integration path proving evaluators can consume current examples and taxonomies
- If API/frontend integration changed:
  - verify artifact paths and payload shapes end to end
  - verify governed runs do not show preview as healthy production

Post-Change Smoke Tests
- Runner and contract smoke:
  - `python3 src/training/scripts/run_hana_pipeline.py --help`
  - verify the documented/default entrypoint resolves to the Simula runner
- Schema and artifact smoke:
  - generate or stage a representative output set
  - confirm the canonical artifact names exist in the agreed output directory
  - confirm the JSONL and taxonomy outputs match the JSON schemas
- Legacy-path regression smoke:
  - `rg -n "make all|schema_pipeline/data_generator.py|prepare_training_data.py|training/pipeline/output/train.jsonl" src/generativeUI/training-webcomponents-ngx/packages/api-server/src/main.py`
  - expected result after full migration: no live Simula path should depend on those references
- Frontend truthfulness smoke:
  - `rg -n "Preconvert|Parse Templates|Expand|Build SQL|Math.random\\(" src/generativeUI/training-webcomponents-ngx/apps/angular-shell/src/app/pages/pipeline/pipeline.component.ts`
  - expected result after full migration: legacy stage model and fake telemetry should not drive the production Simula experience
- Preview-mode smoke:
  - verify governed production runs do not settle on preview or synthetic data mode
  - verify any preview/demo mode is visibly and operationally marked as non-production

Existing Useful Test Entrypoints
- `python3 -m pytest src/training/pipeline/tests/test_pipeline.py -v --tb=short`
- `python3 -m pytest src/training/tests -v --tb=short`
- If API behavior is touched:
  - `python3 -m pytest src/generativeUI/training-webcomponents-ngx/packages/api-server/tests -v --tb=short`

Failure Conditions That Must Block Completion
- The default path still runs the legacy template pipeline.
- Evaluators still expect fields that runtime models do not provide.
- API still points at legacy dataset refs while the runner writes different artifacts.
- Frontend still displays simulated stages or random throughput as if they were real Simula telemetry.
- Governed runs can finish successfully while using preview fallback paths.
- Artifacts exist but do not validate against the spec-backed schemas.

Working Style
- Be conservative with contracts and explicit with migrations.
- Prefer deleting ambiguity over preserving accidental compatibility.
- When in doubt, make the system more measurable:
  - more explicit artifact names
  - more explicit report structures
  - more explicit tests
  - more explicit failure modes
- If you can specify a concrete verification command, do so.
- Match the operational specificity standard already demonstrated in `src/generativeUI/.clinerules`.

Completion Standard
- The target is not "good enough."
- The target is spec-faithful, operationally wired, schema-valid, test-backed, and observable end to end.
